WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:16.257 --> 00:00:20.223
How do you explain
when things don't go as we assume?

00:00:20.257 --> 00:00:23.223
Or better, how do you explain

00:00:23.257 --> 00:00:27.223
when others are able to achieve things
that seem to defy all of the assumptions?

00:00:27.257 --> 00:00:29.223
For example:

00:00:29.257 --> 00:00:31.223
Why is Apple so innovative?

00:00:31.257 --> 00:00:33.223
Year after year, after year,

00:00:33.257 --> 00:00:36.223
they're more innovative
than all their competition.

00:00:36.257 --> 00:00:38.223
And yet, they're just a computer company.

00:00:38.257 --> 00:00:40.223
They're just like everyone else.

00:00:40.257 --> 00:00:42.457
They have the same access
to the same talent,

00:00:42.457 --> 00:00:43.457
the same agencies,

00:00:43.490 --> 00:00:45.357
the same consultants, the same media.

00:00:45.390 --> 00:00:48.823
Then why is it that they seem
to have something different?

00:00:50.257 --> 00:00:54.223
Why is it that Martin Luther King
led the Civil Rights Movement?

00:00:54.257 --> 00:00:58.223
He wasn't the only man
who suffered in pre-civil rights America,

00:00:58.257 --> 00:01:00.990
and he certainly wasn't
the only great orator of the day.

00:01:01.023 --> 00:01:02.223
Why him?

00:01:02.257 --> 00:01:05.223
And why is it that the Wright brothers

00:01:05.257 --> 00:01:08.223
were able to figure out controlled,
powered man flight

00:01:08.257 --> 00:01:10.423
when there were certainly other teams

00:01:10.423 --> 00:01:13.290
who were better qualified,
better funded --

00:01:13.323 --> 00:01:16.223
and they didn't achieve
powered man flight,

00:01:16.257 --> 00:01:18.223
and the Wright brothers beat them to it.

00:01:18.257 --> 00:01:20.157
There's something else at play here.

00:01:21.390 --> 00:01:25.223
About three and a half years ago,
I made a discovery.

00:01:25.257 --> 00:01:31.223
And this discovery profoundly changed
my view on how I thought the world worked,

00:01:31.257 --> 00:01:35.257
and it even profoundly changed the way
in which I operate in it.

00:01:37.257 --> 00:01:40.223
As it turns out, there's a pattern.

00:01:40.257 --> 00:01:44.223
As it turns out, all the great inspiring
leaders and organizations in the world,

00:01:44.257 --> 00:01:47.257
whether it's Apple or Martin Luther King
or the Wright brothers,

00:01:47.290 --> 00:01:51.223
they all think, act and communicate
the exact same way.

00:01:51.257 --> 00:01:55.223
And it's the complete opposite
to everyone else.

00:01:55.257 --> 00:01:57.223
All I did was codify it,

00:01:57.257 --> 00:02:01.223
and it's probably
the world's simplest idea.

00:02:01.257 --> 00:02:03.257
I call it the golden circle.

00:02:11.557 --> 00:02:14.223
Why? How? What?

00:02:14.257 --> 00:02:16.223
This little idea explains

00:02:16.257 --> 00:02:20.223
why some organizations and some leaders
are able to inspire where others aren't.

00:02:20.257 --> 00:02:22.223
Let me define the terms really quickly.

00:02:22.257 --> 00:02:25.223
Every single person, every single
organization on the planet

00:02:25.257 --> 00:02:27.990
knows what they do, 100 percent.

00:02:29.257 --> 00:02:31.223
Some know how they do it,

00:02:31.257 --> 00:02:33.957
whether you call it
your differentiated value proposition

00:02:33.957 --> 00:02:36.223
or your proprietary process or your USP.

00:02:36.257 --> 00:02:40.990
But very, very few people or organizations
know why they do what they do.

00:02:41.023 --> 00:02:43.223
And by "why" I don't mean
"to make a profit."

00:02:43.257 --> 00:02:45.223
That's a result. It's always a result.

00:02:45.257 --> 00:02:47.223
By "why," I mean: What's your purpose?

00:02:47.257 --> 00:02:49.690
What's your cause? What's your belief?

00:02:49.723 --> 00:02:53.223
Why does your organization exist?

00:02:53.257 --> 00:02:55.623
Why do you get out of bed in the morning?

00:02:55.657 --> 00:02:58.223
And why should anyone care?

00:02:58.257 --> 00:03:00.157
As a result, the way we think, we act,

00:03:00.190 --> 00:03:02.990
the way we communicate
is from the outside in, it's obvious.

00:03:03.023 --> 00:03:05.723
We go from the clearest thing
to the fuzziest thing.

00:03:05.757 --> 00:03:09.223
But the inspired leaders
and the inspired organizations --

00:03:09.257 --> 00:03:12.857
regardless of their size,
regardless of their industry --

00:03:12.890 --> 00:03:15.990
all think, act and communicate
from the inside out.

00:03:17.790 --> 00:03:19.223
Let me give you an example.

00:03:19.257 --> 00:03:22.657
I use Apple because they're easy
to understand and everybody gets it.

00:03:22.657 --> 00:03:25.223
If Apple were like everyone else,

00:03:25.257 --> 00:03:28.757
a marketing message from them
might sound like this:

00:03:28.757 --> 00:03:30.257
"We make great computers.

00:03:31.257 --> 00:03:35.223
They're beautifully designed,
simple to use and user friendly.

00:03:35.257 --> 00:03:36.557
Want to buy one?"

00:03:37.457 --> 00:03:38.457
"Meh."

00:03:38.490 --> 00:03:40.223
That's how most of us communicate.

00:03:40.257 --> 00:03:42.757
That's how most marketing
and sales are done,

00:03:42.757 --> 00:03:44.857
that's how we communicate interpersonally.

00:03:44.890 --> 00:03:46.657
We say what we do,

00:03:46.690 --> 00:03:48.457
we say how we're different or better

00:03:48.490 --> 00:03:50.323
and we expect some sort of a behavior,

00:03:50.357 --> 00:03:52.323
a purchase, a vote, something like that.

00:03:52.357 --> 00:03:53.623
Here's our new law firm:

00:03:53.657 --> 00:03:56.090
We have the best lawyers
with the biggest clients,

00:03:56.090 --> 00:03:57.723
we always perform for our clients.

00:03:57.757 --> 00:03:59.223
Here's our new car:

00:03:59.257 --> 00:04:01.890
It gets great gas mileage,
it has leather seats.

00:04:01.923 --> 00:04:03.090
Buy our car.

00:04:03.123 --> 00:04:04.223
But it's uninspiring.

00:04:04.257 --> 00:04:06.890
Here's how Apple actually communicates.

00:04:08.257 --> 00:04:13.223
"Everything we do,
we believe in challenging the status quo.

00:04:13.257 --> 00:04:16.223
We believe in thinking differently.

00:04:16.923 --> 00:04:18.690
The way we challenge the status quo

00:04:18.723 --> 00:04:21.223
is by making our products
beautifully designed,

00:04:21.257 --> 00:04:23.223
simple to use and user friendly.

00:04:23.257 --> 00:04:25.890
We just happen to make great computers.

00:04:25.923 --> 00:04:26.990
Want to buy one?"

00:04:28.157 --> 00:04:29.457
Totally different, right?

00:04:29.490 --> 00:04:31.423
You're ready to buy a computer from me.

00:04:31.457 --> 00:04:33.657
I just reversed
the order of the information.

00:04:33.690 --> 00:04:37.557
What it proves to us is
that people don't buy what you do;

00:04:37.590 --> 00:04:39.990
people buy why you do it.

00:04:39.990 --> 00:04:44.223
This explains why
every single person in this room

00:04:44.257 --> 00:04:47.223
is perfectly comfortable buying
a computer from Apple.

00:04:47.257 --> 00:04:49.223
But we're also perfectly comfortable

00:04:49.257 --> 00:04:52.223
buying an MP3 player from Apple,
or a phone from Apple,

00:04:52.257 --> 00:04:54.223
or a DVR from Apple.

00:04:54.257 --> 00:04:56.790
As I said before,
Apple's just a computer company.

00:04:56.823 --> 00:05:00.223
Nothing distinguishes them structurally
from any of their competitors.

00:05:00.257 --> 00:05:03.690
Their competitors are equally qualified
to make all of these products.

00:05:03.723 --> 00:05:05.223
In fact, they tried.

00:05:05.257 --> 00:05:08.223
A few years ago, Gateway
came out with flat-screen TVs.

00:05:08.257 --> 00:05:10.690
They're eminently qualified
to make flat-screen TVs.

00:05:10.723 --> 00:05:13.223
They've been making
flat-screen monitors for years.

00:05:13.257 --> 00:05:14.823
Nobody bought one.

00:05:17.923 --> 00:05:23.223
Dell came out with MP3 players and PDAs,

00:05:23.257 --> 00:05:25.223
and they make great quality products,

00:05:25.257 --> 00:05:28.223
and they can make perfectly
well-designed products --

00:05:28.257 --> 00:05:30.057
and nobody bought one.

00:05:30.090 --> 00:05:32.523
In fact, talking about it now,
we can't even imagine

00:05:32.557 --> 00:05:34.090
buying an MP3 player from Dell.

00:05:34.123 --> 00:05:36.323
Why would you buy one
from a computer company?

00:05:36.357 --> 00:05:37.957
But we do it every day.

00:05:37.990 --> 00:05:40.457
People don't buy what you do;
they buy why you do it.

00:05:40.490 --> 00:05:46.023
The goal is not to do business
with everybody who needs what you have.

00:05:46.057 --> 00:05:50.090
The goal is to do business with people
who believe what you believe.

00:05:51.257 --> 00:05:52.890
Here's the best part:

00:05:52.923 --> 00:05:55.223
None of what I'm telling you
is my opinion.

00:05:55.257 --> 00:05:58.223
It's all grounded
in the tenets of biology.

00:05:58.257 --> 00:06:00.223
Not psychology, biology.

00:06:00.257 --> 00:06:02.990
If you look at a cross-section
of the human brain,

00:06:03.023 --> 00:06:05.657
from the top down,
the human brain is actually broken

00:06:05.690 --> 00:06:07.223
into three major components

00:06:07.257 --> 00:06:10.223
that correlate perfectly
with the golden circle.

00:06:10.257 --> 00:06:13.223
Our newest brain, our Homo sapien brain,

00:06:13.257 --> 00:06:15.223
our neocortex,

00:06:15.257 --> 00:06:17.223
corresponds with the "what" level.

00:06:17.257 --> 00:06:19.223
The neocortex is responsible

00:06:19.257 --> 00:06:23.223
for all of our rational
and analytical thought and language.

00:06:23.257 --> 00:06:26.223
The middle two sections make up
our limbic brains,

00:06:26.257 --> 00:06:29.223
and our limbic brains are responsible
for all of our feelings,

00:06:29.257 --> 00:06:32.223
like trust and loyalty.

00:06:32.257 --> 00:06:34.390
It's also responsible
for all human behavior,

00:06:34.423 --> 00:06:36.223
all decision-making,

00:06:36.257 --> 00:06:39.223
and it has no capacity for language.

00:06:39.257 --> 00:06:42.223
In other words, when we communicate
from the outside in,

00:06:42.257 --> 00:06:45.390
yes, people can understand vast
amounts of complicated information

00:06:45.423 --> 00:06:48.223
like features and benefits
and facts and figures.

00:06:48.257 --> 00:06:50.223
It just doesn't drive behavior.

00:06:50.257 --> 00:06:52.357
When we can communicate
from the inside out,

00:06:52.390 --> 00:06:54.623
we're talking directly
to the part of the brain

00:06:54.623 --> 00:06:56.223
that controls behavior,

00:06:56.257 --> 00:07:00.223
and then we allow people to rationalize it
with the tangible things we say and do.

00:07:00.257 --> 00:07:02.823
This is where gut decisions come from.

00:07:02.823 --> 00:07:06.223
Sometimes you can give somebody
all the facts and figures,

00:07:06.257 --> 00:07:08.990
and they say, "I know
what all the facts and details say,

00:07:08.990 --> 00:07:10.523
but it just doesn't feel right."

00:07:10.557 --> 00:07:13.090
Why would we use that verb,
it doesn't "feel" right?

00:07:13.123 --> 00:07:15.890
Because the part of the brain
that controls decision-making

00:07:15.923 --> 00:07:17.223
doesn't control language.

00:07:17.257 --> 00:07:18.723
The best we can muster up is,

00:07:18.757 --> 00:07:20.790
"I don't know. 
It just doesn't feel right."

00:07:20.823 --> 00:07:24.223
Or sometimes you say you're leading
with your heart or soul.

00:07:24.257 --> 00:07:26.923
I hate to break it to you,
those aren't other body parts

00:07:26.957 --> 00:07:28.223
controlling your behavior.

00:07:28.257 --> 00:07:30.390
It's all happening here
in your limbic brain,

00:07:30.423 --> 00:07:33.723
the part of the brain that controls
decision-making and not language.

00:07:33.723 --> 00:07:36.223
But if you don't know
why you do what you do,

00:07:36.257 --> 00:07:39.223
and people respond
to why you do what you do,

00:07:39.257 --> 00:07:42.223
then how will you ever get people

00:07:42.257 --> 00:07:44.290
to vote for you,
or buy something from you,

00:07:44.323 --> 00:07:46.223
or, more importantly, be loyal

00:07:46.257 --> 00:07:49.223
and want to be a part
of what it is that you do.

00:07:49.257 --> 00:07:52.323
The goal is not just to sell
to people who need what you have;

00:07:52.323 --> 00:07:55.223
the goal is to sell to people
who believe what you believe.

00:07:55.257 --> 00:07:59.223
The goal is not just
to hire people who need a job;

00:07:59.257 --> 00:08:02.223
it's to hire people
who believe what you believe.

00:08:02.257 --> 00:08:04.390
I always say that, you know,

00:08:04.390 --> 00:08:10.223
if you hire people just because they can
do a job, they'll work for your money,

00:08:10.257 --> 00:08:12.057
but if they believe what you believe,

00:08:12.057 --> 00:08:14.523
they'll work for you with blood
and sweat and tears.

00:08:14.523 --> 00:08:18.223
Nowhere else is there a better example
than with the Wright brothers.

00:08:18.257 --> 00:08:21.857
Most people don't know
about Samuel Pierpont Langley.

00:08:21.890 --> 00:08:24.223
And back in the early 20th century,

00:08:24.257 --> 00:08:27.390
the pursuit of powered man flight
was like the dot com of the day.

00:08:27.423 --> 00:08:29.223
Everybody was trying it.

00:08:29.257 --> 00:08:32.223
And Samuel Pierpont Langley
had, what we assume,

00:08:32.257 --> 00:08:34.923
to be the recipe for success.

00:08:34.957 --> 00:08:36.657
Even now, you ask people,

00:08:36.690 --> 00:08:39.290
"Why did your product
or why did your company fail?"

00:08:39.323 --> 00:08:41.590
and people always give
you the same permutation

00:08:41.590 --> 00:08:43.023
of the same three things:

00:08:43.057 --> 00:08:46.023
under-capitalized, the wrong people,
bad market conditions.

00:08:46.057 --> 00:08:48.857
It's always the same three things,
so let's explore that.

00:08:49.690 --> 00:08:51.223
Samuel Pierpont Langley

00:08:51.257 --> 00:08:54.223
was given 50,000 dollars
by the War Department

00:08:54.257 --> 00:08:56.223
to figure out this flying machine.

00:08:56.257 --> 00:08:57.823
Money was no problem.

00:08:57.857 --> 00:09:00.223
He held a seat at Harvard

00:09:00.257 --> 00:09:03.257
and worked at the Smithsonian
and was extremely well-connected;

00:09:03.290 --> 00:09:05.223
he knew all the big minds of the day.

00:09:05.257 --> 00:09:09.223
He hired the best minds money could find

00:09:09.257 --> 00:09:11.223
and the market conditions were fantastic.

00:09:11.257 --> 00:09:14.223
The New York Times
followed him around everywhere,

00:09:14.257 --> 00:09:16.223
and everyone was rooting for Langley.

00:09:16.257 --> 00:09:19.257
Then how come we've never heard
of Samuel Pierpont Langley?

00:09:19.757 --> 00:09:21.890
A few hundred miles away in Dayton, Ohio,

00:09:22.823 --> 00:09:24.223
Orville and Wilbur Wright,

00:09:24.257 --> 00:09:28.223
they had none of what we consider
to be the recipe for success.

00:09:28.257 --> 00:09:30.223
They had no money;

00:09:30.257 --> 00:09:33.490
they paid for their dream
with the proceeds from their bicycle shop.

00:09:33.523 --> 00:09:35.790
Not a single person
on the Wright brothers' team

00:09:35.823 --> 00:09:37.223
had a college education,

00:09:37.257 --> 00:09:39.223
not even Orville or Wilbur.

00:09:39.257 --> 00:09:42.223
And The New York Times
followed them around nowhere.

00:09:42.257 --> 00:09:44.223
The difference was,

00:09:44.257 --> 00:09:48.223
Orville and Wilbur were driven by a cause,
by a purpose, by a belief.

00:09:48.257 --> 00:09:52.223
They believed that if they could
figure out this flying machine,

00:09:52.257 --> 00:09:54.057
it'll change the course of the world.

00:09:55.657 --> 00:09:57.590
Samuel Pierpont Langley was different.

00:09:57.623 --> 00:10:00.223
He wanted to be rich,
and he wanted to be famous.

00:10:00.257 --> 00:10:02.223
He was in pursuit of the result.

00:10:02.257 --> 00:10:04.223
He was in pursuit of the riches.

00:10:04.257 --> 00:10:06.223
And lo and behold, look what happened.

00:10:06.223 --> 00:10:09.790
The people who believed
in the Wright brothers' dream

00:10:09.790 --> 00:10:12.223
worked with them with blood
and sweat and tears.

00:10:12.257 --> 00:10:14.223
The others just worked for the paycheck.

00:10:14.257 --> 00:10:17.457
They tell stories of how every time
the Wright brothers went out,

00:10:17.490 --> 00:10:19.490
they would have to take
five sets of parts,

00:10:19.523 --> 00:10:22.523
because that's how many times
they would crash before supper.

00:10:23.923 --> 00:10:27.923
And, eventually, on December 17th, 1903,

00:10:27.957 --> 00:10:30.223
the Wright brothers took flight,

00:10:30.257 --> 00:10:32.290
and no one was there
to even experience it.

00:10:32.323 --> 00:10:34.423
We found out about it a few days later.

00:10:36.023 --> 00:10:40.023
And further proof that Langley
was motivated by the wrong thing:

00:10:40.057 --> 00:10:42.390
the day the Wright brothers took flight,

00:10:42.423 --> 00:10:43.423
he quit.

00:10:43.457 --> 00:10:45.223
He could have said,

00:10:45.257 --> 00:10:47.223
"That's an amazing discovery, guys,

00:10:47.257 --> 00:10:50.223
and I will improve
upon your technology," but he didn't.

00:10:50.257 --> 00:10:53.857
He wasn't first, he didn't get rich,
he didn't get famous, so he quit.

00:10:54.957 --> 00:10:57.457
People don't buy what you do;
they buy why you do it.

00:10:57.490 --> 00:10:59.223
If you talk about what you believe,

00:10:59.257 --> 00:11:02.223
you will attract those
who believe what you believe.

00:11:02.257 --> 00:11:05.590
But why is it important to attract
those who believe what you believe?

00:11:07.657 --> 00:11:10.223
Something called the law
of diffusion of innovation,

00:11:10.223 --> 00:11:12.757
if you don't know the law,
you know the terminology.

00:11:12.757 --> 00:11:17.223
The first 2.5% of our population
are our innovators.

00:11:17.257 --> 00:11:21.457
The next 13.5% of our population
are our early adopters.

00:11:22.523 --> 00:11:24.357
The next 34% are your early majority,

00:11:24.390 --> 00:11:26.723
your late majority and your laggards.

00:11:27.690 --> 00:11:30.223
The only reason these people
buy touch-tone phones

00:11:30.257 --> 00:11:32.490
is because you can't buy
rotary phones anymore.

00:11:32.523 --> 00:11:34.223
(Laughter)

00:11:34.257 --> 00:11:37.223
We all sit at various places
at various times on this scale,

00:11:37.257 --> 00:11:40.223
but what the law of diffusion
of innovation tells us

00:11:40.257 --> 00:11:45.223
is that if you want mass-market success
or mass-market acceptance of an idea,

00:11:45.257 --> 00:11:49.223
you cannot have it
until you achieve this tipping point

00:11:49.257 --> 00:11:52.223
between 15 and 18 percent
market penetration,

00:11:52.257 --> 00:11:55.223
and then the system tips.

00:11:55.257 --> 00:11:58.490
I love asking businesses,
"What's your conversion on new business?"

00:11:58.523 --> 00:12:01.157
They love to tell you,
"It's about 10 percent," proudly.

00:12:01.190 --> 00:12:03.323
Well, you can trip
over 10% of the customers.

00:12:03.357 --> 00:12:05.290
We all have about 10% who just "get it."

00:12:05.323 --> 00:12:07.023
That's how we describe them, right?

00:12:07.057 --> 00:12:09.523
That's like that gut feeling,
"Oh, they just get it."

00:12:09.557 --> 00:12:11.990
The problem is: How do you
find the ones that get it

00:12:12.023 --> 00:12:14.657
before doing business
versus the ones who don't get it?

00:12:14.690 --> 00:12:18.223
So it's this here, this little gap
that you have to close,

00:12:18.257 --> 00:12:20.623
as Jeffrey Moore calls it,
"Crossing the Chasm" --

00:12:20.657 --> 00:12:24.223
because, you see, the early majority
will not try something

00:12:24.257 --> 00:12:28.223
until someone else has tried it first.

00:12:28.257 --> 00:12:31.223
And these guys, the innovators
and the early adopters,

00:12:31.257 --> 00:12:33.457
they're comfortable
making those gut decisions.

00:12:33.457 --> 00:12:36.223
They're more comfortable
making those intuitive decisions

00:12:36.257 --> 00:12:40.223
that are driven by what
they believe about the world

00:12:40.257 --> 00:12:42.223
and not just what product is available.

00:12:42.257 --> 00:12:44.890
These are the people who stood
in line for six hours

00:12:44.923 --> 00:12:47.057
to buy an iPhone when they first came out,

00:12:47.090 --> 00:12:50.223
when you could have bought one
off the shelf the next week.

00:12:50.257 --> 00:12:52.390
These are the people
who spent 40,000 dollars

00:12:52.423 --> 00:12:55.223
on flat-screen TVs
when they first came out,

00:12:55.257 --> 00:12:57.557
even though the technology
was substandard.

00:12:58.257 --> 00:13:02.223
And, by the way, they didn't do it
because the technology was so great;

00:13:02.257 --> 00:13:04.223
they did it for themselves.

00:13:04.257 --> 00:13:06.223
It's because they wanted to be first.

00:13:06.257 --> 00:13:08.723
People don't buy what you do;
they buy why you do it

00:13:08.757 --> 00:13:12.223
and what you do simply proves
what you believe.

00:13:12.257 --> 00:13:16.223
In fact, people will do the things
that prove what they believe.

00:13:16.257 --> 00:13:21.223
The reason that person bought the iPhone
in the first six hours,

00:13:21.257 --> 00:13:23.223
stood in line for six hours,

00:13:23.257 --> 00:13:25.623
was because of what they believed
about the world,

00:13:25.657 --> 00:13:27.657
and how they wanted everybody to see them:

00:13:27.690 --> 00:13:28.723
they were first.

00:13:28.757 --> 00:13:31.223
People don't buy what you do;
they buy why you do it.

00:13:31.257 --> 00:13:33.223
So let me give you a famous example,

00:13:33.257 --> 00:13:37.823
a famous failure and a famous success
of the law of diffusion of innovation.

00:13:37.857 --> 00:13:39.223
First, the famous failure.

00:13:39.257 --> 00:13:41.223
It's a commercial example.

00:13:41.257 --> 00:13:43.490
As we said before, the recipe for success

00:13:43.523 --> 00:13:46.923
is money and the right people
and the right market conditions.

00:13:46.923 --> 00:13:48.690
You should have success then.

00:13:48.690 --> 00:13:50.223
Look at TiVo.

00:13:50.257 --> 00:13:52.957
From the time TiVo came out
about eight or nine years ago

00:13:52.990 --> 00:13:54.223
to this current day,

00:13:54.257 --> 00:13:57.923
they are the single highest-quality
product on the market,

00:13:57.923 --> 00:13:59.790
hands down, there is no dispute.

00:14:00.857 --> 00:14:02.657
They were extremely well-funded.

00:14:02.690 --> 00:14:04.390
Market conditions were fantastic.

00:14:04.390 --> 00:14:06.223
I mean, we use TiVo as verb.

00:14:06.257 --> 00:14:09.523
I TiVo stuff on my piece-of-junk
Time Warner DVR all the time.

00:14:09.523 --> 00:14:11.590
(Laughter)

00:14:12.057 --> 00:14:14.223
But TiVo's a commercial failure.

00:14:14.257 --> 00:14:16.223
They've never made money.

00:14:16.257 --> 00:14:18.223
And when they went IPO,

00:14:18.257 --> 00:14:20.223
their stock was at about 30 or 40 dollars

00:14:20.257 --> 00:14:22.690
and then plummeted,
and it's never traded above 10.

00:14:22.723 --> 00:14:25.223
In fact, I don't think
it's even traded above six,

00:14:25.257 --> 00:14:27.223
except for a couple of little spikes.

00:14:27.257 --> 00:14:29.590
Because you see, when TiVo
launched their product,

00:14:29.623 --> 00:14:32.223
they told us all what they had.

00:14:32.257 --> 00:14:35.723
They said, "We have a product
that pauses live TV,

00:14:35.723 --> 00:14:40.223
skips commercials, rewinds live TV
and memorizes your viewing habits

00:14:40.257 --> 00:14:42.057
without you even asking."

00:14:43.423 --> 00:14:45.223
And the cynical majority said,

00:14:45.257 --> 00:14:47.223
"We don't believe you.

00:14:47.257 --> 00:14:49.790
We don't need it. We don't like it.

00:14:49.823 --> 00:14:50.890
You're scaring us."

00:14:51.957 --> 00:14:53.223
What if they had said,

00:14:53.257 --> 00:14:58.223
"If you're the kind of person
who likes to have total control

00:14:58.257 --> 00:15:01.223
over every aspect of your life,

00:15:01.257 --> 00:15:04.223
boy, do we have a product for you.

00:15:04.257 --> 00:15:06.223
It pauses live TV, skips commercials,

00:15:06.257 --> 00:15:08.423
memorizes your viewing habits, etc., etc."

00:15:09.123 --> 00:15:11.623
People don't buy what you do;
they buy why you do it,

00:15:11.657 --> 00:15:15.023
and what you do simply serves
as the proof of what you believe.

00:15:15.823 --> 00:15:19.857
Now let me give you a successful example
of the law of diffusion of innovation.

00:15:21.257 --> 00:15:24.223
In the summer of 1963,

00:15:24.257 --> 00:15:28.223
250,000 people showed up
on the mall in Washington

00:15:28.257 --> 00:15:29.923
to hear Dr. King speak.

00:15:31.423 --> 00:15:34.223
They sent out no invitations,

00:15:34.257 --> 00:15:37.223
and there was no website
to check the date.

00:15:37.257 --> 00:15:39.223
How do you do that?

00:15:39.257 --> 00:15:41.390
Well, Dr. King
wasn't the only man in America

00:15:41.423 --> 00:15:43.823
who was a great orator.

00:15:43.857 --> 00:15:46.023
He wasn't the only man
in America who suffered

00:15:46.057 --> 00:15:47.823
in a pre-civil rights America.

00:15:47.857 --> 00:15:50.223
In fact, some of his ideas were bad.

00:15:50.257 --> 00:15:51.290
But he had a gift.

00:15:52.223 --> 00:15:55.490
He didn't go around telling people
what needed to change in America.

00:15:55.523 --> 00:15:57.823
He went around
and told people what he believed.

00:15:57.857 --> 00:16:01.223
"I believe, I believe, I believe,"
he told people.

00:16:01.257 --> 00:16:03.790
And people who believed what he believed

00:16:03.823 --> 00:16:07.223
took his cause, and they made it
their own, and they told people.

00:16:07.257 --> 00:16:09.290
And some of those people
created structures

00:16:09.323 --> 00:16:11.823
to get the word out to even more people.

00:16:11.857 --> 00:16:15.223
And lo and behold,
250,000 people showed up

00:16:15.257 --> 00:16:19.490
on the right day at the right time
to hear him speak.

00:16:20.257 --> 00:16:22.757
How many of them showed up for him?

00:16:24.590 --> 00:16:25.623
Zero.

00:16:26.257 --> 00:16:28.223
They showed up for themselves.

00:16:28.257 --> 00:16:30.957
It's what they believed about America

00:16:30.990 --> 00:16:33.223
that got them to travel
in a bus for eight hours

00:16:33.257 --> 00:16:36.223
to stand in the sun in Washington
in the middle of August.

00:16:36.257 --> 00:16:39.290
It's what they believed,
and it wasn't about black versus white:

00:16:39.323 --> 00:16:41.657
25% of the audience was white.

00:16:42.657 --> 00:16:46.257
Dr. King believed that there are
two types of laws in this world:

00:16:46.290 --> 00:16:50.223
those that are made by a higher authority
and those that are made by men.

00:16:50.257 --> 00:16:53.223
And not until all the laws
that are made by men

00:16:53.257 --> 00:16:56.057
are consistent with the laws
made by the higher authority

00:16:56.090 --> 00:16:58.023
will we live in a just world.

00:16:58.023 --> 00:17:00.457
It just so happened
that the Civil Rights Movement

00:17:00.457 --> 00:17:04.223
was the perfect thing to help him
bring his cause to life.

00:17:04.257 --> 00:17:07.223
We followed, not for him,
but for ourselves.

00:17:07.257 --> 00:17:09.557
By the way, he gave
the "I have a dream" speech,

00:17:09.590 --> 00:17:11.557
not the "I have a plan" speech.

00:17:11.590 --> 00:17:15.223
(Laughter)

00:17:15.257 --> 00:17:18.457
Listen to politicians now,
with their comprehensive 12-point plans.

00:17:18.457 --> 00:17:20.223
They're not inspiring anybody.

00:17:20.257 --> 00:17:23.223
Because there are leaders
and there are those who lead.

00:17:23.257 --> 00:17:27.223
Leaders hold a position
of power or authority,

00:17:27.257 --> 00:17:30.257
but those who lead inspire us.

00:17:31.790 --> 00:17:34.157
Whether they're individuals
or organizations,

00:17:34.157 --> 00:17:37.223
we follow those who lead,
not because we have to,

00:17:37.257 --> 00:17:39.090
but because we want to.

00:17:40.057 --> 00:17:44.490
We follow those who lead, not for them,
but for ourselves.

00:17:45.757 --> 00:17:48.223
And it's those who start with "why"

00:17:48.257 --> 00:17:52.990
that have the ability
to inspire those around them

00:17:53.023 --> 00:17:55.223
or find others who inspire them.

00:17:56.457 --> 00:17:57.623
Thank you very much.

00:17:57.657 --> 00:17:59.257
(Applause)

